AB  - It is a privilege and pleasure to engage the close readings and thoughtful queries of the five commentators who contributed to this forum on Duress. They provide an opportunity to reflect on - and beyond - my own preoccupations, and thus offer a welcome challenge. Since Duress went to press Israel has proudly declared itself an apartheid state; the French press and public have once again, as both did 20 years ago, pronounced France increasingly free of prejudice and in multiracial harmony in light of its World Cup victory. In the small city of Nantes, 450 refugees from North Africa squatting with minimal access to sanitary facilities in the city's rat-infested central park are rounded up by riot police. Europe has rescinded whatever partial welcome it once granted to refugees, and heightened its ever more aggressive security apparatus. And with insidious petulance Donald Trump promises to shut down the government if he doesn't get funding for "his" wall. The United States continues to descend into Philip Roth's fascist nightmare (as fantasised in his novel The Plot Against America), resuscitating a policy of "child removal' - once a staple of imperial governance widely practised and now condemned across the world. One might argue that colonial conditions and imperial formations have little to do with these developments, but as both Duress and the commentators here attest, there is strong reason to disagree.
