AB  - Mars Hill Church‚Äîa large multisite church centered in Seattle‚Äîcommissioned research examining the perceptions of and objections to Christianity among unchurched and dechurched adults in the United States. ‚Äò‚ÄòUnchurched‚Äô‚Äô persons were defined as those who attend worship services every few months or less and who did not regularly attend worship services growing up. The ‚Äò‚Äòdechurched‚Äô‚Äô were defined as persons who attend worship services every few months or less but who regularly attended services as a child. Data were gathered using both a quantitative and a qualitative component. For the quantitative portion, GfK Public Affairs and Corporate Communications conducted a nationwide telephone survey using random digit dialing (RDD). To qualify for the study, respondents had to be between 18 and 44 years of age and be either unchurched (n = 259) or dechurched (n = 741) as defined above. The surveys were conducted on landlines and cell phones between late April and early June 2013 and took roughly 12 min each. Saurage Marketing Research conducted the qualitative portion of the research, which consisted of eight focus groups with unchurched and dechurched U.S. adults between the ages of 18 and 44 years. The groups were held in Austin, Boston, Phoenix, and San Francisco. In each city, two focus groups were conducted: one with women and another with men. The groups involved 68 respondents in total, who were selected to maintain diversity in terms of educational level and church experience for each group.The findings reveal that a majority of survey respondents describe themselves as spiritual, whether ‚Äò‚Äòvery‚Äô‚Äô (21 %) or ‚Äò‚Äòsomewhat‚Äô‚Äô (35 %). Being at least somewhat spiritual is much more common among the dechurched (61 %) than among the unchurched (42 %). The respondents tended to understand Christianity as mostly about acceptance, tolerance, and the Golden Rule, and they criticized Christians for not living in accordance with those values. While some tried to avoid over-generalizing, most respondents viewed Christians as off-putting. Many think that Christianity and Christian leaders play on fear of death and the unknown, and that Christianity is primarily an existential ‚Äò‚Äòcrutch‚Äô‚Äô that they do not need. For most respondents, their perceptions of church are derived from their exposure to the Catholic Church, Evangelical mega-churches, and television preachers.The primary objection to Christianity across all focus groups and demographics was that some Christians are too intolerant (55 % of survey respondents indicated this as an objection). Beliefs about sexuality and reproduction‚Äîespecially gay marriage and abortion‚Äîwere the second leading objection (50 %), followed in third place by the role of Christianity in U.S. politics (49 %).
