AB  - The premiere episode of¬ American Horror Story: Coven¬ (2013‚Äì14) offers a glimpse into the life of the nineteenth‚Äêcentury New Orleans socialite Madame Delphine Lalaurie before she is punished for her crimes by the ‚ÄúVoodoo Queen,‚Äù Marie Laveau (Angela Bassett), who gifts her with immortality before burying her alive beneath her own home. Lalaurie is then catapulted into the present when she is rescued by Fiona Goode (Jessica Lange), the dying leader‚Äîcalled the Supreme‚Äîof a witch coven who wants to know how Lalaurie has managed to stay alive. Lalaurie becomes embroiled in the coven's attempts to rejuvenate itself and with its ongoing conflict with Laveau, who is also immortal. Although her presence allows for many of the most horrific scenes in the show's third season, Lalaurie's character does not add much to the major plotline. What, then, is her primary function? In¬ American Horror Story: Coven, the historical figure and the character of Madame Delphine Lalaurie serves a crucial role in deconstructing the nature of ‚Äúevil‚Äù in women characters. While she would be considered evil in just about any sense, the ‚Äúauthentic‚Äù evil of Madame Lalaurie, based on the facts and folklore of her life, is compounded by the way she is portrayed as either flouting or failing gender norms, both in her own time and in the present. Although she is but one ‚Äúevil‚Äù character among several, the nature of her evil‚Äîstemming as it does from a connection to ‚Äúreal‚Äù history, overt racial bigotry, and a failure to conform to gender norms‚Äîresonates with audiences living in an ostensible postfeminist, postracial moment. She is certainly not the only character who destabilizes naturalized gender roles. But while viewers may find themselves uneasily speculating on the complex portrayal of evil in a character, such as Fiona Goode, Lalaurie's more straightforward evil provides an easy alternative for passing moral judgment because she embodies both failed feminine socialization as well as a racial prejudice that is perceived by white audiences to have long since passed. The combination of failed motherhood (and thus failed femininity), racial bigotry, and a verifiable history of atrocities makes Lalaurie the clear antagonist in a season filled with so‚Äêcalled evil women. Madame Lalaurie thus provides an ‚Äúauthentic‚Äù means of recuperation for mainstream (white) audiences struggling against accusations of ongoing systemic sexism and racism in contemporary society.
